# Rule of the house — `{{PRINCIPAL_SCOPE}}/`

You are inside {{PRINCIPAL_NAME}}'s personal scope as
{{PRINCIPAL_ROLE}} of {{COMPANY_NAME}}. This is the lightest-touch scope
in the brain — {{PRINCIPAL_NAME}} runs the company; the canon here is
their working memory plus the strategic decisions they want logged.

Trust calibration: this scope assumes the principal is the user. If a
different employee somehow lands in this folder, they shouldn't have
read access — that's enforced by GitHub team membership, not by this
file. But this file's tone presumes the principal is reading.

## Read scope

- This folder (`{{PRINCIPAL_SCOPE}}/`) in full.
- All other scopes' canon for context (the principal can read everything).
- The MainBrain at `~/Main{{SLUG}}Brain/` — read-only, as always.

The principal is the only role with full-canon read across the company.

## Write scope

- `{{PRINCIPAL_SCOPE}}/working/` — full power. Strategy notes, meeting
  prep, scratch thinking.
- `{{PRINCIPAL_SCOPE}}/*` (canon) — promotion-gated. Self-approval
  counts here (single-author scope; CODEOWNERS routes to
  `{{PRINCIPAL_NAME}}` themselves), but **the gate still runs** — every
  canon edit produces a PR + audit-log entry, even if the principal
  one-clicks-approves. The friction is the audit trail, not the second
  pair of eyes.
- Append-only on `{{PRINCIPAL_SCOPE}}/.audit-log.md` — every canon
  change writes a one-line entry here automatically.

## Voice

- **First-person, the principal's own voice.** Notes here read as
  {{PRINCIPAL_NAME}}'s thinking, not an institutional voice.
- **Compress aggressively.** The principal reviews this in the margins of
  long days. Tight bullets > loose paragraphs.
- **Bias toward `working/`.** Most strategic notes start as drafts and
  stay there. Promote to canon only when {{PRINCIPAL_NAME}} explicitly
  decides it's worth keeping for the company's record.

## Default outputs

- **Decisions** the principal makes on their own → `{{PRINCIPAL_SCOPE}}/decisions/`.
  Use `wiki-templates/decision.md`. The principal's reasoning, the
  trade-off they accepted, what would change their mind.
- **Meeting prep / debriefs** → `{{PRINCIPAL_SCOPE}}/working/meetings/`. Don't
  promote routine debriefs; only promote ones that contain a decision
  or commitment.
- **Reads on people** → these belong in the MainBrain
  (`~/Main{{SLUG}}Brain/people/`), not in this scope. Stage proposals to
  the MainBrain via the tray, never write directly.
- **Strategy artifacts** the company should inherit (e.g. annual plan,
  org-design changes) → promote to `{{PRINCIPAL_SCOPE}}/strategy/` or to
  `company/decisions/` depending on whether the artifact is principal's
  position vs. company commitment.

## Optional: local-only model

For genuinely sensitive notes (M&A thinking, personnel, legal
exposure), {{PRINCIPAL_NAME}} can mark the file with frontmatter:

```yaml
model: local-only: true
```

The pergamino runtime then routes that file's drafting and review
through a local model (Ollama on the principal's laptop), never an
external API. Use sparingly — local models are slower and weaker. The
default is the standard cloud model.

## Forbidden

- **Writing to the MainBrain.** Even here. The MainBrain is the
  principal's hand-curated zone; staged proposals go through the tray
  at `~/LLM{{SLUG}}Brain/outputs/mainvault-pending/`.
- **Speaking publicly on behalf of the company.** Customer-facing
  copy is its own scope, with its own reviewer.
- **Bypassing the audit log.** Even one-click self-approvals produce
  a PR + entry. If {{PRINCIPAL_NAME}} ever needs to take an action
  that wouldn't audit cleanly, that's the moment to stop and reconsider,
  not to find a workaround.

